{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-detail-js","path":"/blog/qr/","result":{"data":{"file":{"childMarkdownRemark":{"fields":{"slug":"/qr/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"smallQR","date":"December 20, 2023","subtitle":"All you need is a small QR code","slug":"robots","img":{"childImageSharp":{"gatsbyImageData":{"layout":"constrained","placeholder":{"fallback":"data:image/jpeg;base64,"},"images":{"fallback":{"src":"/static/9586d1f9f758cba7e3f09bc8fe66f528/3fbb1/wien.jpg","srcSet":"/static/9586d1f9f758cba7e3f09bc8fe66f528/aa7af/wien.jpg 250w,\n/static/9586d1f9f758cba7e3f09bc8fe66f528/e031f/wien.jpg 500w,\n/static/9586d1f9f758cba7e3f09bc8fe66f528/3fbb1/wien.jpg 1000w,\n/static/9586d1f9f758cba7e3f09bc8fe66f528/f9a5a/wien.jpg 2000w","sizes":"(min-width: 1000px) 1000px, 100vw"},"sources":[{"srcSet":"/static/9586d1f9f758cba7e3f09bc8fe66f528/7b8a1/wien.avif 250w,\n/static/9586d1f9f758cba7e3f09bc8fe66f528/d708b/wien.avif 500w,\n/static/9586d1f9f758cba7e3f09bc8fe66f528/16fd9/wien.avif 1000w,\n/static/9586d1f9f758cba7e3f09bc8fe66f528/20ca0/wien.avif 2000w","type":"image/avif","sizes":"(min-width: 1000px) 1000px, 100vw"},{"srcSet":"/static/9586d1f9f758cba7e3f09bc8fe66f528/002ed/wien.webp 250w,\n/static/9586d1f9f758cba7e3f09bc8fe66f528/15bdf/wien.webp 500w,\n/static/9586d1f9f758cba7e3f09bc8fe66f528/27c85/wien.webp 1000w,\n/static/9586d1f9f758cba7e3f09bc8fe66f528/0dc98/wien.webp 2000w","type":"image/webp","sizes":"(min-width: 1000px) 1000px, 100vw"}]},"width":1000,"height":563}}}},"html":"<table>\n  <tr>\n    <td><H2>smallQR</H2></td>\n    <td><a  class=\"btn btn-primary m-3\" href=\"https://smallqr.pythonanywhere.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">open app</a></td>\n  </tr>\n</table>\n<p>The QR code is a 2D barcode that can contain up to 7089 digits or 4296 characters.\nA traditional QR code is composed by a matrix of black and white squares, that can be read by a camera and decoded by a software.</p>\n<p>Information can be encoded in a QR code in different ways, and the most common is the alphanumeric one.</p>\n<p>A traditional use case for research is to include a QR code in a poster or presentation, so that the audience can scan it and get more information about the topic.</p>\n<p>The problem is that the QR code is usually too big to be included in a poster, and its resolution is too low to be scanned from a distance.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/vignif/smallQR/main/main.png\" alt=\"img\"></p>\n<p>The solution is to encode whatever information we want in a small QR code, and then use a software to enlarge it.</p>\n<p>QR codes have a built-in error correction, so that even if the code is partially damaged, it can still be decoded.\nThe use case described here (a qr code on a poster) does not usually require a high error correction, so we can use a small QR code with a low error correction.</p>\n<p>This small project uses a python library and is deployed on pythonanywhere via a flask wrapper.</p>"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/qr/","next":{"childMarkdownRemark":{"fields":{"slug":"/me/"}}},"previous":null}},"staticQueryHashes":["3248652660","3649515864"],"slicesMap":{}}